    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The State Senate's Transportation Committee recently approved a bill authorizing $10 million in bonding to study where sound barriers are needed most on our highways (''Turning Roar of the Road Into a Whisper,'' April 8). I don't understand why any study is needed.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The State Senate's Transportation Committee recently approved a bill authorizing $10 million in bonding to study where sound barriers are needed most on our highways (''Turning Roar of the Road Into a Whisper,'' April 8). I don't understand why any study is needed.</p>
        <p>Can't the bill's supporters find better uses for our tax dollars? Wooden sound barriers cost $1.3 million per mile, plus site preparation or landscaping. They are marginally effective, graffiti targets, require upkeep and generally mar the landscape. Adding insult to injury, the study will be funded by bonding so future generations can pay for it.</p>
        <p>It doesn't require a crystal ball to forecast traffic growth with an expanding vehicular population. Why should all taxpayers pay for an issue specific to homeowners in proximity to highways, the same highways that meant their homes cost less when purchased?</p>
        <p>George Sherwin  Cos Cob</p>
      </block>
